SENATE BILL 992
C5, Q4 6lr2097
By: Senators Hester, Feldman, Lewis Young, Sydnor, Love, Hettleman, Ready, and
Folden
Introduced and read first time: February 19, 2026
Assigned to: Rules
A BILL ENTITLED
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Public Utilities – Large Load Customers – Registration and Demand Response
3 Program
4 FOR the purpose of requiring a certain large load customer to register with the Public
5 Service Commission before interconnecting with the electric system; establishing the
6 requirements for the registration of a large load customer; requiring that a certain
7 data center be eligible for and considered a “qualified data center” for a certain tax
8 exemption under certain circumstances; requiring the Commission to take certain
9 curtailment actions; requiring the Commission to establish a Demand Response
10 Program for large load customers; and generally relating to large load customers and
11 demand response.
12 BY adding to
13 Article – Public Utilities
14 Section 7–321 and 7–1008
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2025 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 BY repealing and reenacting, without amendments,
18 Article – Tax – General
19 Section 11–239(a)(1), (2), and (6) and (b)
20 Annotated Code of Maryland
21 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
22 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
23 Article – Tax – General
24 Section 11–239(a)(5)
25 Annotated Code of Maryland
26 (2022 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from exist in g l aw . *sb0992*

2 SENATE BILL 992
1 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
2 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
3 Article – Public Utilities
4 7–321.
5 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
6 INDICATED.
7 (2) “DATA CENTER” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 11–239 OF THE
8 TAX – GENERAL ARTICLE.
9 (3) (I) “LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER” MEANS A COMMERCIAL OR
10 INDUSTRIAL CUSTOMER FOR RETAIL ELECTRIC SERVICE THAT:
11 1. HAS OR IS PROJECTED TO HAVE AN AGGREGATE
12 MONTHLY DEMAND OF AT LEAST 25 MEGAWATTS; AND
13 2. HAS OR IS PROJECTED TO HAVE A LOAD FACTOR OF
14 MORE THAN 80%.
15 (II) “LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER” DOES NOT INCLUDE A WATER
16 COMPANY OR SEWAGE DISPOSAL COMPANY.
17 (4) “ON–SITE BACKUP GENERATING FACILITY” MEANS A
18 GENERATING FACILITY THAT IS:
19 (I) NOT CONNECTED TO THE ELECTRIC SYSTEM; AND
20 (II) CAPABLE OF SERVING AT LEAST 50% OF THE LOAD
21 REQUIRED BY A LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER.
22 (B) (1) NOTWITHSTANDING ANY OTHER PROVISION OF LAW, AND IN
23 ADDITION TO THE REQUIREMENTS UNDER § 4–212 OF THIS ARTICLE, A LARGE LOAD
24 CUSTOMER SHALL REGISTER WITH THE COMMISSION IN ACCORDANCE WITH THIS
25 SECTION BEFORE THE LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER INTERCONNECTS WITH THE
26 ELECTRIC SYSTEM.
27 (2) THE COMMISSION MAY CHARGE A REASONABLE FEE FOR THE
28 REGISTRATION UNDER THIS SECTION.

SENATE BILL 992 3
1 (C) (1) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2027, THE COMMISSION, BY ORDER
2 OR REGULATION, SHALL ESTABLISH A PROCESS TO REGISTER LARGE LOAD
3 CUSTOMERS.
4 (2) THE REGISTRATION PROCESS ESTABLISHED BY THE COMMISSION
5 SHALL:
6 (I) APPLY TO NEW OR EXPANDED INTERCONNECTION OF LARGE
7 LOAD CUSTOMERS;
8 (II) REQUIRE A LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER TO DISCLOSE TO THE
9 COMMISSION:
10 1. WHETHER THE CUSTOMER IS PURSUING A
11 SUBSTANTIALLY SIMILAR INTERCONNECTION REQUEST WITH ANOTHER ELECTRIC
12 COMPANY IN THE STATE, OR IN ANOTHER STATE IN THE PJM REGION, AND
13 WHETHER THE APPROVAL OF THE SIMILAR INTERCONNECTION REQUEST WOULD
14 CAUSE THE CUSTOMER TO MATERIALLY CHANGE, DELAY, OR WITHDRAW THE
15 INTERCONNECTION REQUEST;
16 2. WHETHER THE CUSTOMER INTENDS TO:
17 A. ACQUIRE OR BUILD ENERGY GENERATION SOLELY
18 FOR THE CUSTOMER;
19 B. USE ENERGY SOLELY FROM THE ELECTRIC
20 DISTRIBUTION SYSTEM; OR
21 C. BOTH;
22 3. INFORMATION ABOUT THE TYPE OF ON–SITE BACKUP
23 GENERATING FACILITY THAT WOULD BE USED IN THE EVENT OF A SYSTEM OUTAGE;
24 AND
25 4. INFORMATION ABOUT:
26 A. THE AMOUNT OF WATER THAT WOULD BE USED EACH
27 MONTH;
28 B. THE SOURCE OF THE WATER THAT WOULD BE USED;
29 AND

4 SENATE BILL 992
1 C. THE STATUS OF APPLICATIONS FOR WATER
2 APPROPRIATION OR USE PERMITS SUBMITTED TO THE MARYLAND DEPARTMENT OF
3 THE ENVIRONMENT OR A WATER UTILITY OWNED BY THE STATE OR A LOCAL
4 GOVERNMENT;
5 (III) INCLUDE A METHOD FOR THE LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER TO
6 DEMONSTRATE SITE CONTROL FOR THE PROPOSED LOCATION OF THE LARGE LOAD
7 CUSTOMER’S PREMISES THROUGH OWNERSHIP, LEASE CONTROL, OR ANOTHER
8 METHOD ESTABLISHED BY THE COMMISSION;
9 (IV) INCLUDE A UNIFORM FINANCIAL COMMITMENT
10 REQUIREMENT FOR THE LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER’S DEVELOPMENT OF
11 TRANSMISSION INFRASTRUCTURE THAT IS NEEDED TO SERVE THE LARGE LOAD
12 CUSTOMER, INCLUDING:
13 1. SECURITY PROVIDED ON A DOLLAR PER MEGAWATT
14 BASIS, AS SET BY THE COMMISSION;
15 2. TRANSMISSION CONSTRUCTION FINANCING;
16 3. SECURITY UNDER AN AGREEMENT REQUIRING A
17 LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER TO PAY FOR EQUIPMENT OR SERVICES IN ADVANCE OF ANY
18 ESTABLISHED ELECTRIC SERVICE; OR
19 4. ANY OTHER FORM OF FINANCIAL COMMITMENT
20 REQUIRED BY THE COMMISSION;
21 (V) ESTABLISH A PROCEDURE TO ALLOW THE COMMISSION TO
22 ACCESS, WHILE MAINTAINING CONFIDENTIALITY, ANY INFORMATION COLLECTED
23 BY THE INTERCONNECTING ELECTRIC COMPANY FOR TRANSMISSION PLANNING
24 ANALYSES; AND
25 (VI) ESTABLISH ANY OTHER STANDARDS THAT THE
26 COMMISSION CONSIDERS NECESSARY.
27 (D) (1) THE COMMISSION SHALL CERTIFY WHETHER A REGISTRATION
28 UNDER THIS SECTION IS COMPLETE WITHIN 30 DAYS AFTER RECEIVING THE
29 INFORMATION REQUIRED UNDER SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION.
30 (2) IF THE COMMISSION DETERMINES THE REGISTRATION
31 INFORMATION IS INCOMPLETE, THE COMMISSION MAY EXTEND ANY TIME FRAME
32 PROVIDED IN AN ORDER OR REGULATION ESTABLISHING THE REGISTRATION
33 PROCESS UNDER THIS SECTION.

SENATE BILL 992 5
1 (E) A DATA CENTER THAT IS A LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER SHALL BE
2 CONSIDERED A QUALIFIED DATA CENTER FOR THE SALES AND USE TAX EXEMPTION
3 UNDER § 11–239 OF THE TAX – GENERAL ARTICLE IF THE LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER:
4 (1) REGISTERS UNDER THIS SECTION;
5 (2) AGREES TO PARTICIPATE IN THE DEMAND RESPONSE PROGRAM
6 UNDER § 7–1008 OF THIS TITLE; AND
7 (3) (I) PROVIDES ENOUGH BEHIND–THE–METER ENERGY
8 GENERATION TO FULLY OPERATE THE DATA CENTER; OR
9 (II) AGREES TO PURCHASE 100% RENEWABLE ENERGY
10 LOCATED IN THE PJM SERVICE TERRITORY TO FULLY OPERATE THE DATA CENTER.
11 (F) (1) IN ADDITION TO THE REQUIREMENTS UNDER THIS SECTION AND
12 ANY OTHER AUTHORITY OF THE COMMISSION TO CURTAIL OR RESTRICT LOAD TO A
13 CUSTOMER, THE COMMISSION SHALL REQUIRE THAT:
14 (I) ANY CURTAILMENT ORDER FROM PJM ASSIGNED TO AN
15 ELECTRIC COMPANY SERVING ONE OR MORE LARGE LOAD CUSTOMERS BE PASSED
16 THROUGH TO THE LARGE LOAD CUSTOMERS ONLY AND NOT ASSIGNED OR PASSED
17 THROUGH TO ANY OTHER CUSTOMER;
18 (II) ANY FINANCIAL OBLIGATION ASSIGNED TO AN ELECTRIC
19 COMPANY AS A RESULT OF AN ORDER FROM PJM FOR PROCUREMENT OF NEW
20 ENERGY CAPACITY AS A RESULT OF THE INTERCONNECTION OF A LARGE LOAD
21 CUSTOMER BE PASSED THROUGH TO THE LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER;
22 (III) ANY LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER WHOSE INTERCONNECTION TO
23 THE ELECTRIC SYSTEM REQUIRES AN ORDER FROM PJM FOR THE PROCUREMENT
24 OF NEW ENERGY CAPACITY TO PROVIDE FINANCIAL SECURITY TO THE STATE TO
25 ENSURE THAT RESIDENTIAL CUSTOMERS ARE HELD HARMLESS FOR COSTS
26 ASSOCIATED WITH THE NEW ENERGY CAPACITY PROCUREMENT; AND
27 (IV) ANY LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER APPLYING FOR NEW SERVICE
28 PROVIDE TO PJM:
29 1. EXPECTED LOAD USAGE;
30 2. EXPECTED PEAK LOAD USAGE;

6 SENATE BILL 992
1 3. ANY PREEXISTING REQUIREMENTS OR CONTRACTS
2 THAT ARE CONDITIONS PRECEDENT TO COMPLETION OF CONSTRUCTION OR
3 INTERCONNECTION; AND
4 4. ANY OTHER INFORMATION REQUIRED BY THE
5 COMMISSION OR PJM.
6 (2) NOTHING IN PARAGRAPH (1)(I) OF THIS SUBSECTION IS
7 INTENDED TO PROHIBIT:
8 (I) AN ELECTRIC COMPANY FROM TAKING ANY ACTIONS TO
9 MAINTAIN SYSTEM RELIABILITY; OR
10 (II) A LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER FROM PARTICIPATING IN THE
11 DEMAND RESPONSE PROGRAM UNDER § 7–1008 OF THIS TITLE.
12 (G) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2028, AND EACH JANUARY 1 THEREAFTER,
13 THE COMMISSION SHALL REPORT TO THE SENATE COMMITTEE ON EDUCATION,
14 ENERGY, AND THE ENVIRONMENT AND THE HOUSE ENVIRONMENT AND
15 TRANSPORTATION COMMITTEE, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
16 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, ON THE REGISTRATION PROGRAM UNDER THIS SECTION.
17 7–1008.
18 (A) (1) IN THIS SECTION THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
19 INDICATED.
20 (2) “LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 7–321
21 OF THIS TITLE.
22 (3) “PROGRAM” MEANS THE DEMAND RESPONSE PROGRAM.
23 (B) THE COMMISSION SHALL ESTABLISH A DEMAND RESPONSE PROGRAM
24 FOR LARGE LOAD CUSTOMERS.
25 (C) THE COMMISSION SHALL OFFER EACH LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER THAT
26 PARTICIPATES IN THE PROGRAM THE OPTION OF CONTRACTING FOR:
27 (1) 6 NONCONSECUTIVE 4–HOUR PERIODS OF LOAD MANAGEMENT OR
28 DEMAND–SIDE MANAGEMENT TIME SLOTS PER CALENDAR YEAR; OR
29 (2) 10 NONCONSECUTIVE 10–HOUR PERIODS OF LOAD MANAGEMENT
30 OR DEMAND–SIDE MANAGEMENT TIME SLOTS PER CALENDAR YEAR.

SENATE BILL 992 7
1 (D) THE COMMISSION SHALL:
2 (1) DEVELOP A CLEAR COMPENSATION STRUCTURE OR FINANCIAL
3 INCENTIVES FOR PROGRAM PARTICIPATION;
4 (2) ESTABLISH A CLEARLY DEFINED PENALTY SYSTEM FOR
5 NONPERFORMANCE DURING ANY FORCE MAJEURE EVENTS BY A PARTICIPATING
6 LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER;
7 (3) ESTABLISH A DISPUTE RESOLUTION PROCESS; AND
8 (4) ESTABLISH MULTIPLE NOTIFICATION AND COMMUNICATION
9 CHANNELS FOR PARTICIPATING LARGE LOAD CUSTOMERS.
10 (E) EACH ELECTRIC COMPANY SHALL PROVIDE PARTICIPATING LARGE
11 LOAD CUSTOMERS:
12 (1) 24 HOURS OF ADVANCE NOTICE OF POTENTIAL DEMAND
13 RESPONSE PERIODS; AND
14 (2) 30 MINUTES OF NOTICE BEFORE EACH DEMAND RESPONSE
15 PERIOD.
16 (F) THE COMMISSION SHALL ADOPT REGULATIONS THAT:
17 (1) PROHIBIT BEHIND–THE–METER ENERGY STORAGE FACILITIES
18 FROM BEING INCLUDED IN A PARTICIPATING LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER’S LOAD;
19 (2) DEVELOP GUIDELINES AND LIMITATIONS FOR CHARGING
20 BEHIND–THE–METER ENERGY STORAGE FACILITIES DURING CERTAIN PEAK
21 DEMAND, AS DETERMINED BY THE COMMISSION; AND
22 (3) ESTABLISH A METHOD FOR MEASURING A PARTICIPATING LARGE
23 LOAD CUSTOMER’S DEMAND RESPONSE PERFORMANCE IN ACCORDANCE WITH
24 SUBSECTION (G) OF THIS SECTION.
25 (G) IN MEASURING A PARTICIPATING LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER’S DEMAND
26 RESPONSE PERFORMANCE, THE COMMISSION SHALL FACTOR IN:
27 (1) NEW VIRTUAL POWER PLANT AGGREGATION OPTIONS
28 DEVELOPED BY ELECTRIC COMPANIES;

8 SENATE BILL 992
1 (2) FRONT–OF–METER ENERGY STORAGE FACILITIES; AND
2 (3) NONWIRE ALTERNATIVES, INCLUDING GRID ENHANCING
3 TECHNOLOGIES, THAT FEED ELECTRICITY BACK TO THE ELECTRIC SYSTEM.
4 (H) A PARTICIPATING LARGE LOAD CUSTOMER CONSTRUCTING A
5 BEHIND–THE–METER ENERGY STORAGE FACILITY UNDER THE PROGRAM IS EXEMPT
6 FROM THE REQUIREMENTS TO:
7 (1) OBTAIN A CERTIFICATE OF PUBLIC CONVENIENCE AND NECESSITY
8 UNDER § 7–207 OF THIS TITLE; OR
9 (2) OBTAIN COMMISSION APPROVAL UNDER § 7–207.1 OF THIS TITLE.
10 (I) ON OR BEFORE JANUARY 1, 2028, AND EACH JANUARY 1 THEREAFTER,
11 THE COMMISSION SHALL REPORT TO THE SENATE COMMITTEE ON EDUCATION,
12 ENERGY, AND THE ENVIRONMENT AND THE HOUSE ENVIRONMENT AND
13 TRANSPORTATION COMMITTEE, IN ACCORDANCE WITH § 2–1257 OF THE STATE
14 GOVERNMENT ARTICLE, ON THE PROGRAM ESTABLISHED UNDER THIS SECTION.
15 Article – Tax – General
16 11–239.
17 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
18 (2) “Data center” means a building or group of buildings used to house
19 computer systems, computer storage equipment, and associated infrastructure that
20 businesses or other organizations use to organize, process, store, and disseminate large
21 amounts of data.
22 (5) (i) “Qualified data center” means:
23 1. a data center located in the State in which an individual
24 or a corporation, within 3 years after submitting an application for the sales and use tax
25 exemption under this section, has:
26 [1.] A. for a data center located within a Tier I area,
27 invested at least $2,000,000 in qualified data center personal property and created at least
28 five qualified positions; or
29 [2.] B. for a data center located in any other area of the
30 State, invested at least $5,000,000 in qualified data center personal property and created
31 at least five qualified positions; OR

SENATE BILL 992 9
1 2. A DATA CENTER THAT HAS MET THE REQUIREMENTS
2 OF § 7–321(E) OF THE PUBLIC UTILITIES ARTICLE.
3 (ii) “Qualified data center” includes:
4 1. a data center that is a co–located or hosting data center
5 where equipment, space, and bandwidth are available to lease to multiple customers; and
6 2. an enterprise data center owned and operated by the
7 company it supports.
8 (6) (i) “Qualified data center personal property” means personal
9 property purchased or leased to establish or operate a data center.
10 (ii) “Qualified data center personal property” includes:
11 1. computer equipment or enabling software used for the
12 processing, storage, retrieval, or communication of data, including servers, routers,
13 connections, and other enabling hardware used in the operation of that equipment;
14 2. heating, ventilation, and air–conditioning and mechanical
15 systems, including chillers, cooling towers, air–handling units, pumps, energy storage or
16 energy efficiency technology, and other capital equipment used in the operation of that
17 equipment; and
18 3. equipment necessary for the generation, transformation,
19 transmission, distribution, or management of electricity, including exterior substations,
20 generators, transformers, unit substations, uninterruptible power supply systems,
21 batteries, power distribution units, remote power panels, and any other capital equipment
22 necessary for these purposes.
23 (b) The sales and use tax does not apply to the sale of qualified data center
24 personal property for use at a qualified data center if the buyer provides the vendor with
25 evidence of eligibility for the exemption issued by the Comptroller.
26 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
27 1, 2026.

